row3: "" {
  direction: right
  style.stroke: transparent
  style.fill: transparent
  comparison: {
    label: "Performance Comparison"
    width: 900
    table: {
      shape: sql_table
      label: "TLB Flush Method Comparison"
      method: "Method | Scope | Latency | Use Case"
      invlpg_row: "invlpg | 1 page | ~15 cycles | Single PTE update"
      cr3_row: "CR3 reload | All non-global | ~200 cycles | Context switch"
      invlpga_row: "invlpga | ASID pages | ~25 cycles | PCID systems"
      global_row: "Global bit | All non-global | 0 cycles | Kernel pages"
    }
  }
}
row4: "" {
  direction: right
  style.stroke: transparent
  style.fill: transparent
  notes: {
    label: "Implementation Notes"
    width: 900
    content: |md
      ### Key Insights
      1. **Global pages (G bit)** survive CR3 reload — map kernel with G=1 to avoid re-walking page tables on every syscall.
      2. **invlpg is serializing** — it forces the CPU to complete all prior memory operations before continuing.
      3. **CR3 reload on context switch** is unavoidable for process isolation — each process needs its own page directory.
      4. **PCID (Process-Context Identifier)** on modern CPUs allows multiple address spaces in TLB simultaneously, reducing flush frequency.
      5. **TLB shootdown** on SMP: when one CPU modifies a page table, it must notify other CPUs to flush their TLB entries for those pages.
    |
  }
}
